AC   Q01083; Q8SXE0; Q9VIT4;
Protein spitz precursor.
"The Drosophila spitz gene encodes a putative EGF-like growth factor
involved in dorsal-ventral axis formation and neurogenesis.";
"The genome sequence of Drosophila melanogaster.";
"Annotation of the Drosophila melanogaster euchromatic genome: a
systematic review.";
"A Drosophila full-length cDNA resource.";
"The spitz gene is required for photoreceptor determination in the
Drosophila eye where it interacts with the EGF receptor.";
"Regulated intracellular ligand transport and proteolysis control EGF
signal activation in Drosophila.";
"EGF receptor signalling: roles of Star and Rhomboid revealed.";
-!- FUNCTION: Ligand for the EGF receptor (Gurken). Involved in a
    number of unrelated developmental choices, for example, dorsal-
    ventral axis formation, glial migration, sensory organ
    determination, and muscle development. It is required for
    photoreceptor determination.
-!- SUBUNIT: Interacts with Star via the lumenal domain.
-!- INTERACTION:
    Q9VBU0:CG11889; NbExp=1; IntAct=EBI-91342, EBI-130092;
    Q9VJH6:CG13272; NbExp=1; IntAct=EBI-91342, EBI-135782;
-!- SUBCELLULAR LOCATION: Cell membrane; single-pass type I membrane
    protein. Endoplasmic reticulum; endoplasmic reticulum membrane;
    single-pass type I membrane protein. Golgi apparatus; Golgi
    apparatus membrane; single-pass type I membrane protein.
    Note=Relocalization to the Golgi apparatus and the plasma membrane
    is mediated by Star. In the presence of Rhomboid, Spitz is found
    only in the Golgi, not at the cell surface.
-!- TISSUE SPECIFICITY: Expressed throughout the embryo.
-!- PTM: Proteolytic processing by Rhomboid occurs in the Golgi.
    Cleavage takes place within the transmembrane domain close to
    residue 144 and the active growth factor is released.
-!- PTM: N-glycosylated and O-glycosylated.
-!- SIMILARITY: Contains 1 EGF-like domain.
